<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Sharp cut in UK investment by German groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION is exacting a heavy toll on German manufacturing investment in
Britain, which fell by almost half in the first six months of last year to
about Pounds 470m, according to figures published yesterday.
The report, by the German Chamber of Commerce in Britain, shows that
investment in the UK fell to a rate of Pounds 940m a year in the first half
of 1991, down from Pounds 1.8bn the year before and Pounds 1.5bn in 1989.
The chamber said the drop reflected the severity of the UK recession rather
than a diversion of investment into eastern Germany.
The figures are a blow to UK hopes that foreign manufacturing investment
would help to offset cuts imposed by British companies.
However, the survey, covering 361 of the 967 German companies in the UK,
suggests that investment will pick up again once the recession is over.
About 82 per cent of manufacturers said they planned further investments
soon; 19 per cent of companies without manufacturing plants said they
planned to set them up, and most companies were pleased with the return they
had earned on their investment, with labour productivity and with industrial
relations.
In spite of this endorsement of the UK as the second largest recipient of
German investment after the US, German industrialists raised serious doubts
about the long-term outlook for British industrial competitiveness.
Mr Juergen Gehrels, chief executive of the British operations of Siemens,
the electrical and engineering group, said Britain would not be able to
attract foreign investment indefinitely on the basis of low labour costs.
Mr Gehrels said Britain's decision to opt out of the European Community's
social charter was vital to maintaining its attractiveness as a
manufacturing base. However, he warned: 'It may be that Britain cannot yet
afford to join the social charter. But it will have to if it is to become a
modern pluralistic society.'
He said it would prove impossible to win purely on the basis of labour
costs. The chamber's report urges greater investment in training and
transport infrastructure.
The survey found that 82 per cent of German companies which already
manufacture in the UK plan to expand over the next five years by investing
almost Pounds 1bn.
Trends and Views on Direct Investment By German-Owned Companies in the UK.
German Chamber of Industry and Commerce in the UK, Mechlenburg House, 16
Buckingham Gate, London SW1E 6LB. Pounds 30 for non-members.
</TEXT>
