<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Testing time for the new man of
letters - The job facing Alan Johnson as leader of the postal workers' union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALAN TUFFIN inherited a special telephone when he took over as general
secretary of the UCW postal workers' union in 1982.
'That's the hotline. If it rings, it's either the prime minister or the
chancellor of the exchequer,' said Mr Tom Jackson, Mr Tuffin's famously
mustachioed predecessor, as he cleared his desk.
A decade later Mr Tuffin is preparing, in turn, to hand over his office to
Mr Alan Johnson, whose election as UCW general secretary-designate was
announced on Friday.
The telephone - not the vibrant red one might imagine for a hotline, but a
dusty, old-fashioned ivory model - still sits on the desk. It has only rung
once in Mr Tuffin's time as UCW leader. 'Somebody wanted to know if it was
Sainsbury's,' says Mr Tuffin wistfully. 'I've never had the luxury of a
Labour government. I've had to deal with a hostile, anti-trade union
government for all the time I've been general secretary.'
Number 10 no longer quakes at the prospect of postal workers flexing their
industrial muscle. The Christmas card is still played most years, as postal
deliveries are briefly threatened as part of pay negotiating tactics. But
there have been just two national postal strikes in the past two decades -
apart from some stoppages at Crown Post Offices last year, which affected
few people.
If a Labour government is back in power by the time Mr Johnson takes over
next year, the worst of the union's fears on privatisation of the postal
service are unlikely to be realised. However, the union would still face a
number of threats and pressures. They include:
New rules from the European Community that are likely to increase
competition and tighten up on cross-subsidies, for example between letter
and parcel services. The effect might be the loss of Post Office business -
and UCW members - to largely non-unionised private operators.
New technology, which might mean the reduction of postal sorting jobs. UCW
membership has been bolstered in recent years by the growth in postal
volumes; but further technological advances might outstrip volume gains.
That has been the case among another of the union's former strong membership
groups, BT telephone operators.
Internal Post Office reorganisation, including separation of the different
businesses, to which the union is only now beginning to respond.
Fragmentation of bargaining has stretched negotiating resources and, at the
same time, the UCW's local structure is under threat from Post Office
management.
A special union conference next month will discuss how to slim down the
existing 800 branches to about 80. To date, the union has managed to avoid
the kind of political divisions which consume so much energy in some other
unions. A smaller number of more powerful branches might leave the UCW more
vulnerable to factionalism in future.
The need to professionalise and streamline head office bureaucracy. The UCW
elects rather than appoints its officers, a policy meaning that, in many
cases, parallel professional appointments have to be made to ensure a
reasonable degree of head office competence. Management consultants have
recommended changes but a special conference of the union last year rejected
many of the proposals.
Radical internal reorganisation is unlikely until after any merger with the
National Communications Union. Mr Tuffin hopes to see the merger agreed
before he steps down next year; the election of Mr Johnson, who is fervently
pro-merger, increases the chances of that happening.
Combining with the NCU to form a union with about 350,000 members - of which
the UCW will contribute about 200,000 - would not put the merged body into
the super-union league, neither would it ease the difficulties of being
linked to a single sector at a time of great change. A merger would,
however, allow the best use of resources as the search for new membership
groups becomes more urgent.
What of Mr Johnson himself? He is comparatively unknown outside the
communications union world. He did, however, hit the headlines briefly a few
months ago when the union extracted an apology from Reebok, the maker of
training shoes, over advertising posters featuring postmen pursued by dogs.
Mr Johnson is well-known for his sense of humour but, as an ex-postman,
finds jokes about dogs too close to the bone.
He is seen as having great promise - a natural successor to Mr Tuffin, but
from an updated mould. Mr Peter Hain, the UCW's former head of research and
now Labour MP for Neath, thinks Mr Johnson will be 'one of the brightest
stars in the trade union movement'.
Now 41, Mr Johnson is young for the job but, as a man who had three children
by the time he was 20, he has some practice of being ahead of his years. He
was orphaned as a child, narrowly escaping a children's home when it was
decided his older sister should look after him. He is a Queens Park Rangers
fan and assiduously follows The Archers on Radio 4.
Like Mr Tuffin, he came up through the union's ranks and is stoutly
Kinnockite. He is a lucid speaker, reputed to be a quick and meticulous
negotiator, and is said to abhor old-style table thumping. His election
address points out that union members need no 'recitation of the problems
they face; they need to be confident that we have the vitality and ingenuity
to find solutions'.
As for the ivory telephone on what will be his new desk - he plans to keep
it, just in case.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
