FT  22 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour says Britain's recession
'worst in EC' - Prime Minister's Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR attempted yesterday to demolish repeated government claims that the
present recession was international in scope, contrasting the shrinking
British economy with growth in other European countries.
The government hit back with a fresh assault on Labour's taxation and
spending pledges. According to Mr John Major, the prime minister, the
implication of such pledges was that either borrowing would rise to
'unprecedented' levels or taxes would be increased 'to a quite remarkable
extent'.
During a rowdy session of prime minister's questions, Mr Major said that
Labour's policies would ensure 'a longstanding and deep recession in this
country'.
Labour had been 'rumbled' on its spending and tax plans and did not like it,
he said.
He denied that recessionary conditions were confined purely to Britain.
Almost every industrialised country was experiencing 'economic problems', he
said.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, attacked Britain's relative economic
performance, claiming it was the worst in the Community in terms of
unemployment, investment and production.
While other European countries were growing, Britain's economy was
'shrinking' by 2 per cent, he said.
That theme was also pursued at an earlier Labour press conference, when the
party cited figures showing that business closures were running at 2,225 a
week last year.
'All the figures which should be going up are still going down,' said Mr
Gordon Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary. 'All those that should be
going down, including inflation, are still going up.'
Budget submissions sent to the Treasury by industrialists showed
overwhelming support for investment tax allowances, Mr Brown said, but
ministers had ruled out such incentives.
Mr Peter Lloyd, Home Office junior minister, last night accused Labour MPs
of making 'inflammatory' charges that the Asylum Bill to deter bogus
applicants for political asylum in Britain was motivated by racist and
electoral considerations.
The Bill was given a third reading by a government majority of 82 (298-216)
and now goes to the Lords.
</TEXT>
