<DATE>920122
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: The government weighs its pair of
choice dates - Speculation over timing of the election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APRIL 9 or May 7? Both are encircled still in pencil rather than ink in Mr
John Major's diary. But as the general election campaign gathers momentum
his pen is poised over the first.
The message on the Whitehall networks is that, barring disasters, the prime
minister will not delay. Senior ministers do not demur from their officials'
judgment.
One mandarin confessed this week he planned a holiday for late March. The
campaign, he judged, would then be in full swing. Another had stepped up a
detailed analysis of Labour's policies in case, as he put it: 'We get a
Kinnock government sooner rather than later.'
As the decks are cleared, Sir Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary, is
drafting a series of notes on the responsibilities of civil servants once
the election is under way.
At the request of the Treasury, they may include an outline of the role of
civil servants in the presentation of the Budget if Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, presents it after the election has been called.
Some officials have been looking back to the precedent of 1955. In April
that year, Mr 'Rab' Butler, then chancellor, gave his Budget four days after
Sir Anthony Eden had announced the election date.
Those with memories refreshed by a recent Whitehall minute recall that Mr
Butler cut income tax from nine shillings to eight shillings and sixpence in
the pound and raised the tax threshold for a married man from Pounds 210 to
Pounds 240.
Within months of the Conservative victory, however, Mr Butler paid for the
income tax cuts by increasing purchase tax - the 1950s equivalent of VAT. By
the end of the same year Mr Butler had been replaced as chancellor by Mr
Harold Macmillan.
A repeat of that chronology is highly unlikely. If the speculation in
Whitehall proves correct, Mr Lamont will set March 10 as the Budget date. Mr
Major would prefer March 3, but presumably would be loath to overrule the
chancellor. The latter date would give him just enough time to go to the
country on April 9.
So he does not have to commit himself until then. He insists also that, if
necessary, he will stay in Downing Street until the constitutional deadline
of July 9 - in practice, late June.
For its part, Conservative Central Office has long encouraged the view that
May 7, the date of annual local elections, is the most likely choice.
It has the advantage of tidiness and would allow more time for tangible
evidence of the promised economic recovery to emerge. Mr Chris Patten, the
party chairman, and Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, are said to regard it
as the best option.
The view of the Treasury establishment is that the recovery might still be
faltering during an April campaign but the light at the end of the tunnel
would at least be brighter.
Mr Patten, meanwhile, is said to have been weighing several factors, ranging
from the better campaigning weather during late April to the dispersal of
the Liberal Democrat campaign effort between local and general elections on
May 7.
He must also be worried that final poll tax bills will begin to fall through
letter boxes in the last week of March, playing to one of Labour's strengths
during an April 9 campaign.
There are now clear signals, though, that Mr Major is keen to go anyway in
April. Others in the cabinet - including Mr Kenneth Baker, the home
secretary, and Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary - are lining up behind
that judgment.
The arguments are both personal and practical. Although an instinctively
cautious politician, Mr Major has become impatient with delay. As one
insider puts it: 'He has become frustrated by all the agonising. He wants to
get on with the job of being prime minister.'
Nor does he want the embarrassment of 'standing down' party activists when
he makes a keynote speech to the Conservative Central Council meeting in
Torquay on March 14. That would evoke too many memories of the dithering of
Mr James Callaghan in 1978.
There are more practical considerations. The admission by the Treasury that
the economic recovery has once again been delayed has added force to the
argument that the best Mr Major can offer is the promise rather than the
reality of an upturn. Nor does he any longer have the luxury of waiting for
the three-month run of opinion poll leads which provided the trigger for the
1983 and 1987 elections.
That said, the argument runs, nothing is likely to happen in the four weeks
between April 9 and May 7 which would improve Conservative fortunes - and
much might go wrong. More positively, an April poll would leave a
tax-cutting Budget fresh in voters' minds.
A reduction in the basic rate of income tax or a large increase in tax
thresholds would crystallise the taxation issue which Mr Major hopes will
dominate the campaign. And the Budget would provide the philosophical glue
for an election manifesto that still lacks a striking central theme, or big
idea.
Not all are so upbeat. When told that the bookmakers were offering odds of
66:1 against a late June election, one minister said he would probably wager
Pounds 100. Another senior minister advised: 'Put your money on April but
leave yourself a small escape hatch.' Mr Major has done just that.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
