<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Uncertainty hold back Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNCERTAINTY over the outcome of the general election is depressing
confidence and holding back a growth in demand, west Midlands business
leaders warned yesterday.
'There is a certain amount of fear about what is going to happen. This is
bound to create some degree of uncertainty,' said Mr Bryan Townsend,
chairman of Midlands Electricity and vice-chairman of the Confederation of
British Industry's west Midlands regional council.
The council brings together the principal manufacturing and service
companies in a region whose economy is more dependent than any other in the
UK on the health of industry.
Although believing that west Midlands industry is well-placed to profit
'once demands starts to grow', Mr Townsend added that such growth is a
matter of confidence and 'there won't be that confidence while there are the
uncertainties'.
He was speaking in Birmingham after a meeting of the CBI's regional council,
which expressed some optimism about an upturn in the economy during the
second half of this year.
With most plants in the west Midlands working at less than full capacity, as
recent surveys have shown, Mr Townsend effectively ruled out an
investment-led recovery. 'If you're working 20 to 30 per cent below
capacity, new investment is difficult to justify,' he said.
</TEXT>
