<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Spending reported stable at year-end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPECTATIONS of low inflation and reduced fears of unemployment have helped
to stabilise consumer confidence, according to a Gallup/BSL regional
consumer survey published yesterday.
The nationwide survey suggested that consumer spending in the fourth quarter
of last year was little changed from the third quarter. It was 1.5 per cent
lower than in the last quarter of 1990.
The improvement in consumer confidence has been most marked in East Anglia,
the north-west of England and the south-west. The north, east Midlands and
south-east, excluding London, showed improvements above the national
average.
The fear of unemployment, while slowly diminishing over the year, continued
to restrain consumers across the country. Expectations on inflation and the
cost of living improved significantly, however.
For the first time since the middle of last year, households expected their
financial situation to improve over the next 12 months. Only Greater London
and Wales expected them to deteriorate.
In Scotland consumer confidence improved over the year to reach the UK
average by the end of last year. The north-south divide has narrowed in the
recession as unemployment has grown more quickly in the south and house
prices have fallen further, Cambridge Econometrics said yesterday.
It said in a report on regional prospects that on measures such as income
per head and unemployment, the south remained more prosperous.
The report forecast virtually no growth for this year for Greater London -
the region suffering worst in the recession. Scotland, which escaped the
worst of the recession, was predicted to grow faster in the short term than
any of the English regions and Wales.
Gallup/BSL Regional Consumer Survey. BSL, 10 Kendrick Mews, London SW7 3HG.
Pounds 40.
Regional Economic Prospects. Cambridge Econometrics, 21 St Andrew's St,
Cambridge CB2 3AX. Pounds 45.
</TEXT>
