<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONWIDE, the second-largest building society, was ordered yesterday to
pay compensation to an investor who lost money because the society's
publicity failed to make clear that a better savings account existed than
the one in which she was investing, David Barchard writes.
Mr Stephen Edell, the building society ombudsman, ruled against a second
complaint by another investor that he had lost money because a slightly
better 90-day account had been introduced during the period in which he was
required to give notice before withdrawing his money.
Mr Edell said yesterday: 'Fundamentally, it is up to people to look after
their own investments. Investors should be vigilant about their investments,
but I don't think that building societies ought to hide the interest rates
paid on closed accounts.'
The complaints followed an outcry against the society last spring when many
of its savers discovered that they were trapped in a lower 90-day interest
account and could not transfer their funds after a better account had been
introduced.
There was uproar at the society's annual meeting in the summer as members
attacked the directors for not telling them about the better account and not
relaxing the90-day rule for giving notice.
