<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Weak credit demand damps recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND FOR credit remains subdued, providing little sign of any imminent
recovery from the recession, according to Bank of England figures published
yesterday.
Bank and building society lending to the private sector grew by a seasonally
adjusted Pounds 1.1bn last month, about half the figure predicted by the
City, while money supply growth remained weak. That increase in M4 lending
followed a freak Pounds 5.7bn increase in November. It took growth in the
figure back to depressed levels.
The data indicate that the desire of companies and individuals to reduce
debts, rather than to take on new credit, will continue to hold back the
economy.
Narrow money or M0, which mostly comprises notes and coins in circulation
and indicates underlying demand pressures, rose 0.3 per cent in December
compared with November to give a 2.8 per cent increase for the year.
The figure, coming after November's year-on-year rise in M0 of 2.9 per cent,
underlines the fragility of consumer activity and accords with recent data
showing weak retail sales.
Broad money or M4 - cash plus bank and building society deposits - rose by
0.8 per cent in December compared with November.
Last month's year-on-year increase in M4 was 6.2 per cent, up from
November's 5.7 per cent. Much of the change was due to higher monetary
growth prompted by the unexpectedly large increase of Pounds 1.2bn in
government borrowing in December.
The figures from the Bank coincided with a report from Britain's nine
biggest commercial banks, which said that last month they lent a net Pounds
39m to the private sector - after a Pounds 3.5bn figure in November which
has been dismissed as a statistical quirk.
The British Bankers' Association, a trade body for the banks, said
December's figures pointed to 'no upturn in lending'. It said that in the
past nine months manufacturers had repaid more than Pounds 2bn in debts.
Demand from individuals for credit had been 'modest' in recent months.
According to detailed figures from the association - which are not adjusted
for seasonal variations - retailers last month repaid debts worth Pounds
406m and manufacturers reduced their credit overhang by Pounds 674m.
Groups in the financial sector that went against the trend included leasing
com-panies and securities dealers, which took on new credit of Pounds 514m
and Pounds 518m respectively.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
