<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / British Coal streamlining to cost over 1,000 jobs at
Yorkshire pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL yesterday announced plans to cut 1,100 jobs at four collieries
in the Yorkshire area.
It said the cuts at four pits - Kellingley and Prince of Wales near
Pontefract, Sharlston near Wakefield, and Whitemoor, part of the Selby
complex - were intended to increase competitiveness by March next year when
contracts with the power generators expire. It fears it may be priced out of
the market without streamlining.
The numbers, which were released at a regional meeting of British Coal, are
not official but British Coal confirmed that they were indicative. It is
understood that voluntary redundancies will be sought before March 28 this
year when an enhanced payment agreement expires.
Union officials fear the losses could total more than 1,300. Mr Ken
Capstick, vice-chairman of Yorkshire National Union of Mineworkers, said:
'I'm disgusted. This is not rationalising the industry, it's butchering.' He
said he expected more cuts to be announced tomorrow at a meeting of the
company's South Yorkshire group.
Mr Alan Houghton, Selby group director, said: 'The contracts with the
electricity generators expire in March next year and our policy is to make
the Selby group of pits strong enough to claim a major share of the market.'
Mr Houghton will meet NUM leaders at the four pits today to spell out how
they will be affected.
Mr Kevin Barron, shadow energy minister, is understood to have received a
letter from the NUM totalling the job losses. He said: 'The Tories are
determined to kill off everything that doesn't make them a fast buck - even
at the expense of the long-term interests of the country.'
During question time in the Commons yesterday Mr John Major, the prime
minister, expressed regret at the job losses. Responding to Mr Barron, Mr
Major said: 'I am sorry to hear of the job losses to which you refer, but
the only secure future for the coal industry or indeed any other industry is
to put itself in a position where it is producing, at a price people can
afford, something that people want.'
One Selby miner said: 'Miners feel betrayed. They were tempted into taking
on larger mortgages and now they are being kicked in the teeth.'
</TEXT>
