<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Row over running of Lloyd's grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE ARE signs that the leadership of Lloyd's of London is increasingly
isolated in opposing proposed reforms to the way the market is run.
With feeling running high among the market's underwriting and broking
businesses, Lloyd's Council, the insurance market's governing body, may be
forced to backtrack on its initial rejection of a proposal that its
responsibilities for business development should be handed over to a new
market board controlled by Lloyd's agents.
In its 240-page report, published last week, the 14-man task force also
recommended that the council's independence as a regulator should be
reinforced by the appointment of an independent chairman.
On Monday Mr Alan Lord, chief executive, and Mr David Coleridge, chairman,
reiterated their opposition to the task force proposals on governance. Mr
Lord described them as unworkable.
Yesterday Mr Paul Archard, chairman of the Lloyd's Underwriting Agents
Association, which represents more than 150 agencies, said he was 'amazed'
by the council's instant rejection and by Mr Lord's comments. 'The
governance chapter of the task force report is fairly fundamental to other
things we want to achieve,' he said.
Mr Nigel Rogers, managing director of Octavian Group, one of the most
rapidly growing Lloyd's agencies, said: 'I haven't spoken to anyone who
thought that the council was right. The groundswell of opinion means that
they will have to reconsider.'
Mr Chris Burton, joint chief executive of AJ Archer, a listed Lloyd's
agency, described the council's decision as 'very disappointing'. He added:
'I endorse the idea of a market board and I believe this view to be widely
held.'
The Association of Lloyd's Members, which represents more than 9,000 Lloyd's
Names, the individuals whose assets provide the market's capital, says it
will press the council to reverse its decision.
Mr Val Powell, the association's chief executive, said: 'We are in round
three and the boxing could get pretty dirty.'
Names will be urged to attend meetings next month to register their
opposition to the council's stance.
The association saw the task force's proposals as analogous to the two-tier
boards common in Germany, with the council and the market board playing
roles equivalent to those of supervisory and management boards.
The market board was necessary because the business had 'not been driven
properly', it said.
Professor John Kay of the London Business School, a member of the task
force, emphasised the importance of a division of the council's regulatory
and executive management roles. 'I can't think of any business structure
where they are combined,' he said. 'You wouldn't ask the chief executive of
BT to be director-general of Oftel.'
Editorial comment, Page 14
</TEXT>
