<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / NHS funding reform extended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EXTENSION to the controversial element of the health service reforms
allowing family doctors to buy medical treatment on behalf of their patients
was announced yesterday.
But both Labour and the Liberal Democrats said they would end the practice,
known as fundholding.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow health secretary, said: 'The next Labour government
will end GP fundholding; we will do it because we will not tolerate two-tier
lists on which the length of time you wait depends on your GP's budget.'
While Labour portrayed this as standing by its existing position, the Tories
interpreted the opposition's announcement that it was looking at ways of
giving all GPs a greater say in National Health Service planning as 'a total
U-turn'.
Under the government's plans, another 5,000 general practitioners will be
able to become fundholders, controlling the budget for treating their
patients for a range of conditions.
Several pilot projects will be launched, designed to improve the operation
of fundholding and to extend the benefits to all GPs. The announcement was
welcomed as 'a step in the right direction' by the British Medical
Association.
Mr William Waldegrave, health secretary, told the Commons that the first
wave of GP fundholding practices had been a 'clear success'. The changes he
announced were designed to 'allow advantages of fundholding to be enjoyed by
more patients and doctors'.
The fundholding provisions have been one of the most contentious parts of
the government's health service reforms launched in April 1991. Those
reforms removed the right of family doctors to refer patients to the
hospital of their choice. That meant most GP practices could refer patients
for treatment only to hospitals and organisations with which the district
health authority has contracts for services.
However, some 1,700 GPs in larger practices were allowed to become
fundholders controlling part of the budget for treating patients. Those GPs
can effectively refer their cases - about 7 per cent of all NHS patients -
to hospitals of their choice.
The freedom of referral that fundholding practices enjoy extends to only a
limited range of conditions. They include minor and elective surgery, such
as corneal grafts, hernia repairs and varicose-vein stripping. Operations
costing more than Pounds 5,000 are outside the control of fundholders.
Such operations are often the ones with the longest waiting lists, and
delays to them cause most unhappiness to NHS users. Critics predicted that a
two-tier health service would be created by fundholders, who would use their
control of budgets for operations to buy faster treatment for their patients
at the expense of the rest.
That seemed to happen, as some hospitals began to offer special deals to
fundholders' patients - including shorter waiting times. The government
moved quickly to change the rules, but the impression persisted that
fundholders' patients enjoyed benefits denied to others.
That impression was reinforced by the experience of GPs who have become
fundholders. The Twickenham,
south-west London, practice of Dr Ian Wild and partners, who became
fundholders last April, shows how their freedom to refer has been used for
the benefit of patients.
Although the practice cannot buy shorter waiting times than non-fundholding
practices, it still has freedom to shop around on behalf of patients for the
best deal for each operation. The practice has also been able to use its
budget to arrange for services previously available only through hospitals,
to be offered to patients at the local health centre.
The picture is reflected in a study carried out for the King's Fund
Institute by Professor Howard Glennerster of the London School of Economics.
It found that fundholding had shifted the balance of power within the NHS
from the consultant to the GP. The conclusion is that fundholding has often
improved the quality of health service for patients.
Such findings had prompted Labour to tone down its opposition to
fundholding. But as the party is pledged to restore GPs' freedom to refer
patients to the hospital of their choice, Mr Cook believes GPs will lose
interest in the additional bureaucracy of fundholding.
The BMA also says many of Britain's family doctors do not want to become
fundholders.
Labour said yesterday that it was looking at ways of giving all GPs a
greater say in NHS planning and in specifying what hospitals should be
providing. But that would not be on the basis of giving them control of
budgets for treating their patients.
Mr Waldegrave also announced that there would be experiments to see whether
non-fundholding GPs could be given more control over operations.
</TEXT>
