<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Prestwick bid backed by council
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CONSORTIUM bidding to buy Prestwick airport in Scotland from BAA, formerly
the British Airports Authority, is to be offered a loan of up to Pounds 1m
on concessionary terms by Strathclyde Regional Council.
The consortium, Ayrshire Community Airport Project (Acap), said it hoped
shortly to reach agreement with BAA.
It said Federal Express, the US cargo airline that uses Prestwick, had an
option to take a stake in Acap and put a nominee on its board.
Two other companies are interested in acquiring Prestwick, which suffered a
drastic fall in passenger traffic after the government removal in March 1990
of its monopoly on transatlantic flights from Scotland. That led several
airlines to transfer operations to Glasgow.
Last week AAP, a company controlled by Mr Peter Kay, a Scotland-based
businessman, submitted a cash offer of Pounds 4.75m to BAA. It said that
last August BAA was prepared to sell it the airport, but negotiations
lapsed.
British Aerospace, which builds aircraft at Prestwick and wants to keep the
runway open, is also talking to BAA.
Acap is chaired by Mr George Younger, chairman of Royal Bank of Scotland and
Conservative MP for Ayr, and comprises local businessmen and local
authorities.
On Monday the dominant Labour party group on the regional council agreed
that Acap should be offered Pounds 1m over four to five years at 11 per cent
interest.
A possible outcome, according to backers of Acap, is that BAA would sell
Prestwick to BAe, which would then hand over its operation to Acap. Neither
BAA or BAe will comment on that.
Federal Express would not comment on the claim that it had an option to buy
a stake in Acap. It said it would work with whoever the successful bidder
was.
</TEXT>
