<DATE>920122
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Perrier vows to fight Nestle bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOURCE Perrier, the French mineral water and cheese company, yesterday vowed
to fight against the FFr13.42bn (Pounds 1.38bn) bid launched by Nestle, the
Swiss food group, and Indosuez, the French bank.
At the same time, BSN, another force in the French food industry, threw down
the gauntlet to the Agnellis, the Italian industrialists who have mounted a
FFr5.6bn bid for Exor, Perrier's biggest single shareholder. BSN declared
that it would not allow the Agnellis to further increase their investment in
BSN.
Perrier and BSN are embroiled in the battle that is brewing between Nestle,
a traditional ally of BSN, and the Agnellis in the European food industry, a
sector long considered ripe for consolidation.
Mr Jacques Vincent, president of both Perrier and Exor, issued a statement
condemning the bid by Nestle and Indosuez saying that it threatened to
'dismantle Perrier' by dispersing its brands between Nestle and BSN.
He affirmed his support for the Agnelli bid for Exor and for the investment
in Perrier by Saint Louis, the French paper and packaging company associated
with the Agnellis. Both the Exor bid and the Saint Louis investment are
being investigated by the French stock market authorities. Nestle yesterday
said it had obtained court orders to freeze Exor's voting stock in Perrier
and to freeze Saint Louis' voting rights on its 13.8 per cent stake.
The Agnellis have made no secret of their hopes of raising their
indirectly-held 5.8 per cent stake in BSN.
Mr Antoine Riboud, president of BSN, was yesterday quoted in Liberation, the
French newspaper, as saying that he would block any attempt to increase the
Agnelli's investment. Under the terms of an agreement, the Agnellis are
unable to directly or indirectly buy BSN shares without Mr Riboud's consent.
In Paris, BSN's shares slipped by FFr43 to FFr1,111 yesterday after Mr
Riboud's rebuff. Shares in companies linked to the Agnelli family fell
sharply in Milan, depressing prices on the market as a whole.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
