<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Observer: Japan's turn
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan has been better at donating money, rather than its brightest civil
servants, to international organisations. So Kumiharu Shigehara's career as
the OECD's next chief economist will be watched with more than usual
interest.
The 52-year-old Bank of Japan official takes over from David Henderson, who
has been doing the job since 1984. Until now, heads of economics at the
Paris-based group have been either British, like Henderson, or north
Americans. But the Japanese now contribute 24 per cent of the organisation's
budget - a fraction less than the Americans  - and already one of the three
deputy secretary generals is Japanese.
Currently head of a BoJ think-tank called the Institute for Monetary and
Economic Studies, Shigehara has completed three tours of OECD duty, most
recently in 1987-89, when he was director of the policy studies branch.
A tall, donnish man, he is noted abroad for espousing a tough, autonomous
and not excessively pro-American monetary policy at the Bank of Japan. He
has frequently advocated greater deregulation for the Japanese economy and
insists that he will not change his tune in his new post - even on the
sensitive issue of liberalising the rice market.
Fluent in English, he is said to be typical of the new breed of assertive
and international-minded Japanese who are not afraid to speak their mind. In
which case, his appointment will be welcome.
</TEXT>
