<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Observer: Double-booked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What could be more important than listening to Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the
governor of the Bank of England? Tonight's annual dinner of the Manchester
Merchant and International Bankers' Association, it seems.
I hear that there is an embarrassing clash between the timing of the
bankers' booze-up at the Midland Hotel, and the governor's speech at
Manchester Business School's celebrity seminar, a quarter of a mile away.
ABN-Amro Bank's Howard Middleton, chairman for the dinner, assures me that
his keener banker colleagues will be able to squeeze in both events.
However, the figures speak for themselves. There will be almost twice as
many people sitting down to dinner as listening to the governor.
</TEXT>
