FT  22 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's series of programmes offering personal views of history, The Day The
World Changed (8.00), is presented today by Scottish poet Liz Lochead who
chooses February 8 1587, the day Mary Queen of Scots was beheaded. This,
according to Lochead, marked the start of a love-hate relationship between
England and Scotland. For an Englishman the odd thing about this is that
only the Scots seem to be aware of it ..or perhaps 'obsessed by' is better
than 'aware of'.
Western broadcasters have latched on rapidly to the fact they can now make
documentary programmes in the old Warsaw Pact countries and that recent
history is providing a visually dramatic underclass: prostitutes, black
marketeers, and in tonight's Dispatches, thousands of children living on the
streets of St Petersburg (9.00 C4). The second episode of BBC1's biography
of Churchill moves to the period for which he is most famous: World War 2
when, having apparently run his course as a politician, he suddenly turned
out to be the needed inspirational national leader (9.30 BBC1). If you
missed C4's sitcom about a TV newsroom, Drop The Dead Donkey, first time
round, watch now (11.00).
