<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Nationwide group of clubs planned to meet needs of small
businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS for a nationwide network of small-business clubs were announced in
London yesterday.
Durham Small Business Club, which is promoting the idea, hopes the new
network, named Small Business Clubs Nationwide, will start to operate with
20 member clubs on April 1. It is intended for small established businesses,
many of which find chambers of commerce are too expensive or too formal.
According to Mr Tom Moffat, chairman of the Durham Business Club, member
clubs of the new organisation would have to be professionally managed with
full-time staff and a range of activities making them self-supporting -
unlike many existing business clubs which were run on a part-time, voluntary
basis.
Clubs would pay Pounds 2,500 to join the national organisation plus Pounds 5
of their annual Pounds 35 members' subscription to maintain the central
organisation. Mr Moffat said the new network needed at least 20 members to
raise the Pounds 50,000 required for public limited company status but could
start on an unincorporated basis with 10 to 12 members.
At a conference to launch the plan in London yesterday 10 representatives of
existing business clubs, training and enterprise councils and local
authorities said they were interested. A second conference is to be held in
Durham tomorrow.
Mr Moffat said chambers of commerce had reacted cautiously to the plan and
were watching developments. He believed business clubs would complement
rather than compete with the chambers. They might eventually form part of a
three-tier business support network with start-ups helped by enterprise
agencies, smaller established businesses belonging to a club and larger
businesses belonging to a chamber.
Few businesses take steps to reduce the risk of bad debts or to encourage
their customers to pay on time, according to a survey by Barclays Commercial
Services (BCS), the bank's factoring subsidiary.
Four out of five businesses polled said they had no form of credit
protection cover for their invoices even though late payment and non-payment
were significant causes of business failure. Only one in four said they
offered a discount for early settlement.
BCS surveyed 298 businesses, of which 29 per cent were engaged in
manufacturing, 26 per cent in retailing and 21 per cent in services. Just
over half had sales of less than Pounds 2.5m and 10 per cent sales of Pounds
2.5m to Pounds 10m.
</TEXT>
