<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Airlines link for Vilnius service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE European airlines start this week regular scheduled services to
Vilnius, the capital of the newly independent republic of Lithuania which is
seeking to expand economic ties with the west, writes Paul Betts, Aerospace
Correspondent.
Scandinavian Airlines System (SAS), Swissair and Austrian Airlines have for
the first time co-ordinated services to the same city, operating a joint
office and station and jointly recruiting staff.
The move marks a strengthening of the so-called European Quality Alliance
airline partnership which is designed to enhance the competitive position of
the three medium-sized airlines against larger European rivals like British
Airways, Lufthansa and Air France.
The flights - from Copenhagen, Zurich and Vienna - will allow a daily
service to Vilnius from one of the three cities, except on Wednesday.
Lithuania is anxious to attract western investment to modernise and expand
the Vilnius airport. A big problem facing western carriers setting up
operations in the Baltic region is the lack of adequate ground and
telecommunications infrastructure.
Yesterday's launch of the first SAS flight from Copenhagen to Vilnius also
marks a further expansion of the Scandinavian carrier's operations in the
Baltics.
</TEXT>
