<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / London Stock Exchange: BAe falls after twin setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace (BAe) fell heavily early in the session on weekend press
reports, later confirmed by the company, that the finance director was to
resign and that BAe faced an Pounds 80m claim from Asda over an agreement
concerning Burwood House, a 50 per cent jointly owned property operation.
BAe said it expected to reach an agreement over the claim very soon and had
made provisions for the losses.
Mr Sandy Morris of County NatWest said: 'Problems on the property side are
not a surprise, but it is disappointing that further problems have emerged.'
The market took the view that the finance director's departure was further
fall-out from last year's Pounds 432m disastrous rights issue at the
company. An analyst commented: 'The market has been demanding that further
heads must roll and they have now got one.' Mr Chris Avery at Smith New
Court simply called today's news 'another couple of disappointments for this
accident-prone company'.
Bargain hunters, however, ensured that the shares recovered from the day's
worst, eventually ending 12 off at 302p on turnover of 4.6m. At their worst
the stock touched 288p. Asda had an unexceptional day. The stock firmed a
penny to 36 1/2 p on volume of 12m.
British Gas busy
Shares in British Gas improved 3 to 246p on heavy turnover of 7m, with much
of the buying coming from Smith New Court. There was a story that Gas may be
considering the spin-off of a large part of its industrial gas marketing
operation in a move that would allow it to meet the gas regulator's market
objectives without undue damage to shareholder value.
Mr Steve Turner, energy specialist at Smith, said that after the creation of
such independent companies they would be given to Gas's existing holders,
perhaps on a one-for-one basis, or alternatively floated on the stock
market.
Vodafone active
A big placing of Vodafone shares, said to have been carried out by James
Capel, left the stock as the most heavily traded in the market. The Seaq
ticker revealed a block of 4.9m shares dealt at 352p and another similar
sized block traded at 355p.
The deals, carried out at substantial discounts to the ruling market price,
left Vodafone 8 lower at 363p. Volume was a heavy 12m.
The placing underlines a cautious tone on the shares, which had brightened
in the last quarter of 1991 as signs emerged that the cellular market was
picking up. However, the recovery has failed to materialise and analysts
have again been bearish. This month both BZW and Phillips &amp; Drew have turned
cautious on the shares.
Kingfisher falters
Government statistics showing poor retail sales for December, as well as a
forecast cut by one securities house, affected Kingfisher, which fell 10
before rallying with the market to close a net 3 off at 494p in a depressed
stores sector.
County Natwest lowered its profits prediction for 1991 to Pounds 207.3m from
Pounds 214m, mainly in reaction to competitive pressures in the
do-it-yourself market and its Comet electrical goods chain.
The whole sector was weak after the government announced that UK retail
sales fell a provisional seasonally-adjusted 1 per cent in December, giving
a year-on-year decline of 0.4 per cent.
Recent Footsie constituent WH Smith 'A' lost 12 to 461p ahead of interim
results on January 29, while Marks and Spencer declined 6 to 296p.
Publisher Reed International was weak at the expense of Pearson after
securities house SG Warburg published a hefty re-evaluation of the media
sector yesterday. Reed receded 5 to 523p while Pearson improved 10 to 765p.
The 20-page document will be the basis of a series of meetings with
institutional clients over the coming weeks. Warburg reduced its 1992
forecast for Reed by Pounds 10m to Pounds 220m and that for next year by
Pounds 15m to Pounds 258m on consideration of currency factors.
It argues that although Reed's outperformance was justified, there is a case
for 'near-term profit-taking'. On the other hand, it reasons that: 'The
strength of Pearson's balance sheet will continue to underpin the price (of
the shares).'
Pharmaceuticals company Glaxo rose 26 to 864p on a reassessment of the
sector following heavy selling last week and good news on one of its
products. The company reported that it had been granted a licence to market
its Serevent anti-asthma drug in Italy.
There was a further announcement that the company had sold 30 of its
pharmaceuticals brands to drugs company Medeva, which moved up 12 to 228p on
the news.
Fisons rallied 19 to 353p, with the shares receiving added encouragement
ahead of its research and development meeting.
Securities houses SG Warburg and Kleinwort Benson were also said to be
discussing the company with clients. Warburg refused to comment but Mr Ian
White of Kleinwort said he had been repeating his recent buy stance on the
stock.
Wellcome, up 16 at 1050p, was helped by a forecast upgrade from Smith New
Court, which has raised its estimate for the year ending in August by Pounds
10m to Pounds 500m.
A sharp rise in Abbey National last week was reversed after securities house
UBS Phillips &amp; Drew cut its forecast for the bank's profits. The shares lost
8 1/2 to 290p.
UBS reduced its 1992 figure by Pounds 60m to Pounds 635m and its dividend
forecast to 11.15p from 11.75p. It changed its stance from hold to trading
sell. The house believes the recent cut in the mortgage rate will squeeze
margins and the bank will suffer more than previously thought from high
mortgage arrears. UBS was an aggressive seller of Abbey and a buyer of TSB
following well-received results last week. TSB gained 3 to 132 1/2 p.
Conglomerate Lonrho regained lost ground on hopes that the group will hold
its annual dividend at 16p in spite of an expected drop in profits when it
announces full-year results on Thursday. The shares rose 14 to 164p with
7.6m traded.
James Wilkes jumped 30 to 189p after the company confirmed market
speculation that it had received a bid approach.
Rank Organisation moved ahead 19 to 635p as unconfirmed reports said that
the leisure group had sold its Royal Garden Hotel for between Pounds 60m to
Pounds 70m.
Overseas investors, particularly Japanese, were sellers of electricity
issues. National Power lost 2 1/2 to 138 1/2 p but PowerGen ended 2 firmer
at 149p following brisk turnover of 9.2m and 7.6m shares respectively.
Activity in the building and construction sector was again dominated by the
Steetley bid for Redland, with the former losing gains made on Friday.
Positive sentiment had been prompted by market talk of other parties
entering the fray, with ECC interest in Steetley favourite. However, a
weekend statement by ECC denying the speculation left Steetley 4 cheaper at
377p.
Redland gained 4 to 477p, while ECC put on 9 to 494p.
Buy notes from BZW, among others, helped Blue Circle add 9 at 259p.
Profit-taking in Meyer International left the builders supplier down 12 at
411p.
From today, the Financial Times will publish the gross dividend yield on the
FT-SE 100 index. It will appear each day in the panel at the bottom of the
left-hand columns of the front page. The yield on the FT Ordinary index will
continue to appear on this page as before.
The yield calculation is the same as that used in the FT-Actuaries All-Share
index. It is obtained by multiplying total gross dividends payable of the
index constitutents by their number of shares in issue, and dividing the
result by the total market capitalisation of the companies in the index. The
resulting figure is multiplied by 100 to give a percentage rate.
'Running gross dividends' are used: last final dividend plus latest interim
dividend, or vice versa, with the tax credit added. The approach differs
from that used in the London Share Service pages, where the yield is based
on the last annual gross dividend.
