<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LATE burst of activity in the stock index futures market enlivened what
had otherwise been reported to be a dull session, writes Joel Kibazo.
The March contract opened at a premium of 33 and buyers were seen. The
upward direction of the contract did not last and there was a wave of
mid-morning selling, further encouraged by the release of disappointing
retail sales figures for the Christmas period.
A poor opening on Wall Street reinforced the dull market mood and a weak
finish was expected. However, minutes before the close a recovering Wall
Street and an order for 50 contracts triggered heavy buying. That was
followed by another large buying order. Independent traders were left short,
generating a large squeeze in the last half-hour of trading and pushing the
underlying cash market higher. March closed at 2,593 for a premium of 49 to
the cash market and around 27 points above its estimated fair value premium
to cash, but turnover was a meagre 4,432.
In traded options, volume reached 28,343. The FT-SE Index had 4,285
contracts dealt. Storehouse was the busiest stock option with 2,305 lots
traded. Asda was the second most active on 2,185 contracts transacted.
</TEXT>
