<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities ease in light trade
after last week's gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER LAST week's strong gains, US stock markets were in subdued form
yesterday with share prices tending to ease. Trading was relatively light
because of the semi-official Martin Luther King Day holiday, which closed
federal offices, banks and the bond markets, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 10.95 at 3,254.03.
The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 receded 2.50 to 416.36, while the Nasdaq composite
of over-the-counter stocks ran into heavy profit-taking and fell 7.47 to
619.38. New York SE turnover came to 181m shares, while declines outpaced
rises by 943 to 743.
The market often opens lower on the first day after the monthly expiration
of stock futures and options contracts. Last Friday the Dow had been boosted
to a new high by trading linked to the expirations on derivative markets,
and so some downward correction yesterday had been anticipated.
Moreover, in the absence of fresh economic and big corporate news, those
investors not away for the one-day holiday chose to take it easy, only
occasionally dipping into the market to take some profits earned during the
recent sharp advance.
Upjohn fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 41 1/2 amid a deepening row over
alleged side effects of its best selling sleeping drug, Halcion. It issued
strong condemnations of researchers who claim to have found that Halcion
causes serious psychiatric side effects among some users.
In the same sector, Pfizer rose initially on the news that researchers in
Boston have reported on their preliminary human tests with an experimental
drug for adult-onset diabetes, but eventually succumbed to market-wide
selling and ended down Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 76 1/4 . The drug is licensed
to Pfizer and another company.
Other drug stocks, which were heavily sold last week on rotational trading
by investors switching between sectors, were mixed. Glaxo put on Dollars
3/4 to Dollars 31 5/8 but Schering-Plough declined Dollars 5/8 to Dollars 60
7/8 .
UAL dropped Dollars 4 to Dollars 152 in the wake of last Friday's warning
that it expected to report the largest three-month loss in its history for
the fourth quarter.
Raytheon, which shot to fame during the Gulf war as the maker of the Patriot
anti-missile weapon, weakened Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 87 1/4 on reports
that it has submitted a bid for General Dynamics' Cessna aircraft unit.
Dynamics retreated Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 59 1/2 .
On the over-the-counter market, Landmark Graphics tumbled Dollars 4 1/2 to
Dollars 20 3/4 after reporting fiscal second-quarter income of 30 cents a
share, up from a year earlier but still below market estimates.
Canada
TORONTO failed to establish a clear trend although trading was fairly heavy.
The composite index eased 2.6 to close at 3,655.7, but rises narrowly
outnumbered falls by 329 to 280 after a volume of 30.5m shares, down from
Friday's 34.9m.
The gold group had the day's biggest gain among the sub-indices, a rise of
1.5 per cent.
Canadian Pacific Forest fell CDollars 1 1/4 to CDollars 26 1/4 . The company
said it will issue 8.5m common shares at CDollars 26.50 apiece. It currently
has about 44m shares outstanding.
Bombardier 'A' rose CDollars 1 1/2 to CDollars 31 1/2 and the 'B' added
CDollars  7/8 at CDollars 31 1/2 . The company's president said he is
confident that negotiations will be successfully completed for Bombardier to
buy a stake in Boeing's de Havilland unit.
</TEXT>
