<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Money Markets: UK rates close level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK money rates eased slightly in the face of a substantial liquidity
shortage yesterday, writes Simon London.
The Bank of England forecast a shortage of Pounds 1.55bn in early morning,
later revised up to Pounds 1.7bn. The main factor was maturing treasury
bills and earlier assistance totalling Pounds 1.38bn.
However, following the volatility of short rates last week which saw
overnight money trade as high as 30 per cent, market participants were keen
to take assistance
In early assistance, the Bank of England injected a hefty Pounds 1.251bn.
The main component was the purchase of Pounds 679m paper for resale to the
market at 10 7/16 per cent in equal instalments on February 5 and 6. The
balance was mostly in the form of band 1 bank bills, purchased at 10 3/8 per
cent.
In late morning an additional Pounds 200m was injected, again through the
purchase of short-dated band 1 bills at 10 3/8 per cent. Afternoon
assistance comprised the buying of Pounds 248m band 1 bills, with a late
injection of Pounds 90m.
This was sufficient to drive short rates down to well below Friday's closing
levels. Overnight unsecured funds traded down to 8 per cent in
mid-afternoon, from 11-10 3/4 per cent late on Friday. However, later in the
day short rates firmed and finished at 10 3/4 - 1/2 per cent.
The March short sterling contract on the London International Financial
Futures Exchange traded up to 89.77, from 89.70 on Friday. This implies base
rates of 10.33 per cent by the spring from a current rate of 10.5 per cent.
In Frankfurt, call money continued to trade around 9.40/50 per cent,
unchanged from the levels seen last week. Tax payments continued to drain
funds from the market, but there is sufficient liquidity to keep rates
comfortably below the Lombard rate.
The Bank of Japan injected more liquidity than expected yesterday, leading
analysts to comment that the authorities were ensuring an ample supply of
funds against the background of a weak stock market. The Nikkei stock market
index fell 407.5 points to close at 20,913.8, the lowest level since October
1990.
In its regular operations, the Bank of Japan injected Y1,600bn funds, more
than the forecast shortage of Y1,430bn. This ensured easier short money
rates. Call money traded down to 5 9/16 per cent, from 5 5/8 per cent on
Friday.
</TEXT>
