<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / International Company News: Textron wins Cessna with bid of
Dollars 600m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEXTRON, the Rhode Island-based aerospace and financial services group,
announced last night that it had won the auction for Cessna Aircraft
Company, which manufactures business jets and cargo planes and is currently
owned by General Dynamics.
General Dynamics, the second largest US defence group, has been shrinking
its operations recently and concentrating on core businesses. It put Cessna
up for sale last October, and only last week Dassault Aviation, the French
maker of business and military jets, announced that it would be making an
offer for the General Dynamics subsidiary.
Textron has agreed to pay Dollars 600m in cash for Cessna, whichGeneral
Dynamics bought for Dollars 660m 1985.
Cessna, which is based in Wichita, Kansas, had sales last year of around
Dollars 820m. It has produced general aviation aircraft for much of its
history but, in the early 1980s, refocused operations on its Citation
business jet and Caravan utility turboprop aircraft. The latter is used for
both cargo and passenger service, finding customers amongst the express
package delivery companies, such as Federal Express.
</TEXT>
