<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Lloyd's chief might have quit if governance had changed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF LONDON chief executive Mr Alan Lord said yesterday that he might
have had to quit last week if a proposal to change the way the insurance
market is governed had been accepted.
Although the Council, Lloyd's governing body, agreed the bulk of a series of
reforms put forward by a 14-strong task force, it rejected the proposed
separation of its regulatory and business development functions.
The change is regarded by the chairman of the task force, Mr David Rowland,
as being among the most important of 65 suggestions.
Last week the Association of Lloyd's Members, which represents more than
9,000 Lloyds Names, also criticised the decision to reject it.
Mr Lord said acceptance would have delayed implementation of other reforms
suggested by the task force. These include a modification of the principle
of unlimited liability for Names, the individuals whose capital supports
underwriting at Lloyd's.
But yesterday, hinting that Lloyd's had understated its case last week, Mr
Lord said: 'If we'd gone along this route I wouldn't have felt able to go
along with it. Its the mystery of the month why they came out with it.'
Mr David Coleridge, chairman of Lloyd's, added fuel to the fire by
describing some of the task force's thinking on governance as 'codswallop'.
The task force advocated the creation of a market board, made up mainly of
representatives of underwriting businesses, which should have responsibility
for developing the market's business strategy. The Council - on which
outside Names and nominees already have a majority - would retain its
regulatory responsibilities, although it would be strengthened by the
appointment of an independent chairman.
Mr Lord said the creation of the market board would be 'retrogressive'
because it would have reduced the effectiveness of the regulatory structure
introduced by the Lloyd's Act of 1982. At the Council meeting the proposals
had been rejected because 'in structural terms they made no sense at all.'
Mr Lord said: 'To divide the thing into two with a market board which
instituted market changes and a regulatory body snapping round its heels
trying to regulate what has already been done doesn't work.'
He also said Lloyd's would have been deprived of a 'sovereign body'. 'You
can't run an outfit with two heads,' he added.
Outhwaite backed, Page 8
</TEXT>
