<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Councils face move to extend benefits
for part-timers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN COMMUNITY rules on equal pay will almost certainly require UK
councils to introduce sick-pay schemes for their many part-time workers,
mostly women, who are paid less than Pounds 52 a week.
Mr Stephen Bubb, assistant secretary of the Labour-dominated Association of
Metropolitan Authorities, said yesterday the association felt that it might
not be treating part-time workers fairly and might be falling foul of EC
legislation.
Almost 70 per cent of the 800,000 manual workers in local government are
part-timers, and many of those are paid less than Pounds 52 a week. A
requirement to provide sick-pay for several hundred thousand workers
previously excluded could significantly increase pay bills.
Mr Bubb said it was difficult to determine how many workers would be
affected by an extension of sick-pay schemes, but the equality audit being
conducted by employers and unions would probably provide an answer.
The exclusion of part-time workers from sick-pay and other benefits is
likely to be a main theme of this year's pay bargaining on behalf of council
manual workers. A local-government employers' consultation paper, to be
issued this week, says the manual workers' interest is likely to shift to
equality issues in this year's negotiations.
'They can be expected in particular to pursue the position of part-timers'
conditions of service,' says the paper. It continues: 'Already there are
indications of concerted union efforts, through industrial tribunal
references, to have the national agreement's effective exclusion from
occupational sick-pay of part-time manual workers earning less than Pounds
52 a week declared illegal.'
Underlining that point, the National Union of Public Employees (Nupe)
yesterday launched a test case at Leeds Industrial Tribunal on behalf of
1,000 school-meals staff employed by North Yorkshire County Council.
Nupe said that following competitive tendering of the school meals service
the council dismissed all its staff and offered them back their jobs with
lower pay rates, reduced holidays and little or no sick-pay.
Nupe is challenging the action under British and European equal-pay laws.
The union said the women had been treated differently from groups of male
workers, such as those in highway maintenance, who were also subject to
competitive-tendering laws.
Union leaders at Ford New Holland, the tractor maker owned by Ford and Fiat,
will meet today to consider whether to order industrial action after the
company said it would not increase a three-year pay deal including a 4 per
cent rise in the first year from last November. Management was yesterday
warned of the possibility of one-day or two-day strikes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
