<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Training shunted to the slow track -
Gloomy predictions from the voluntary sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST February Mr Patrick Coldstream, a director of two charitable companies
providing training for the unemployed, met Mrs Sarah Hogg, head of the prime
minister's policy unit.
He predicted grave consequences for training providers from government
changes in funding arrangements, and warned that voluntary bodies such as
his would be hit particularly hard. To some extent his prophecy has been
fulfilled.
The voluntary sector's share of places is estimated by the National Council
for Voluntary Organisations (NCVO) to have fallen from 25 per cent of the
places on Employment Training, the scheme for unemployed adults, in 1990-91
to 15 per cent in 1991-92. Its share of Youth Training, the scheme for
16-to-18-year-olds, has been less affected, from 7 per cent to 6.5 per cent.
Charities are thought to comprise 5 per cent of the 7,200 organisations
which train 16-to-18-year-olds on the two schemes. The remaining training
providers include local authorities and commercial organisations.
Debate has focused on the voluntary sector because of the announcement a
fortnight ago that Fullemploy, a 19-year-old voluntary-sector training
organisation catering mainly for ethnic minorities had gone into
liquidation. Mr Coldstream helped to set up Fullemploy, which is seeking a
purchaser.
This week administrators were called to Apex Trust, a leading
voluntary-sector provider, to see if liquidation could be averted. A
financial crisis was caused there by a demand from the Department of
Employment for repayment of Pounds 250,000. Apex trains mainly ex-offenders
as well as being a lobby group whose backers include Dr George Carey,
archbishop of Canterbury.
Mr Coldstream says: 'If organisations as powerfully supported as Apex Trust
and Fullemploy are collapsing, the whole network of voluntary-sector
providers, many of which are small and perhaps less well-managed, must be
vulnerable.'
He says that cuts in funding of training schemes and changes in payment
regimes over the past year were not always the immediate cause of problems
even though they left 'no margin for financial error' among organisations.
Unlike commercial training bodies, they have no capital.
'Fullemploy had a bad management patch in the late 1980s,' admits Mr
Coldstream. 'It now has an excellent new management, but the organisation
was never offered the chance to rebuild with confidence.'
Fullemploy had managed to salvage its financial position but was refused a
government grant because of Home Office fears about its solvency.
Grand Metropolitan Community Services, a large training provider set up by
the food and drink group, is considering the possibility of acquiring some
Fullemploy contracts. It is fortunate in having core funding from its parent
company, and has acquired several small training organisations over the past
few years.
But the next few months may see the demise of smaller training providers as
ministers set out to negotiate new contracts with Training and Enterprise
Councils (Tecs) for 1992-93.
The problems affecting training providers, particularly those training the
disadvantaged, began when the government gave responsibility for training to
the 82 employer-led Tecs in England and Wales.
The real value of government grants for Youth Training and Employment
Training has been eroded since the early 1980s. The value of grants to Youth
Training has been halved since 1983.
When Tecs started, the government took their arrival as an opportunity to
ask employers to shoulder even more of the financial burden of the two
training schemes. In addition, payment for Youth Training became
output-related, which meant that up to 25 per cent of payments to Tecs from
the government were related to people gaining qualifications. This provoked
problems among training providers, particularly those assisting
special-needs groups. Many had their training places reduced. Some places
were lost, but in some Tec areas contracts went to more general providers of
training which offered Tecs more competitive rates.
The NCVO claims those at special disadvantage have suffered
disproportionately from cuts in funding in 1991-92. In May it estimated
that, in the halving of adult training places in the voluntary sector, 75
per cent of the cuts involved people with special needs.
Mrs Anne Weinstock, chief executive of The Rathbone Society, a
Manchester-based voluntary organisation, says Tec directors, faced with
funding cuts, are tempted to take a tougher commercial line.
A second change that upset providers in the voluntary sector is the change
by Tecs to funding providers in arrears. Before the creation of Tecs the
government paid in advance.
Concern over this has been expressed by Bridge Group, which represents many
providers in the voluntary sector. It says many Tecs have been reluctant to
offer providers grants to tide them over the funding changes. Tecs retort
that providers would be financially liable if they defaulted. The response
of Tecs to the effect of the likely demise of specialist providers,
including Apex, is mixed. In part the argument includes division over
whether special groups need special training or should be integrated.
Some Tecs say that they foresee few practical difficulties in finding
alternative providers for training places. Apex, they claim, had always been
well-paid for its trainees, and other training providers would jump at their
contracts.
Others see problems. Mr Michael Hanson, the chief executive of South London
Tec, faces the task of finding about 100 new training places if Fullemploy
is not rescued.
More importantly, Mr Hanson believes that the expertise of specialist
providers is not readily bought.
He says: 'Fullemploy in particular has built up a particular skill in
training its client group, and it also built confident links with employers.
That is not easily replaced.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
