<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine gives Budget pledge -
Poll Tax Bills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, insisted yesterday that the
government would not 'fix' Budget proposals to delay the sending out of poll
tax bills until after a general election.
Any change to the poll tax would be made on its merits and not to hold up
bills, he said on BBC radio.
His remarks followed an attack by Mr Bryan Gould, the shadow environment
secretary, that in choosing the timing of the election the Tories faced the
'ticking timebomb' of bills being sent out during the campaign, whether the
election was on April 9 or May 7.
The level of the poll tax was likely to be nearer Pounds 300 than the
government's planned target of Pounds 257, Mr Gould said.
The government has wide powers to 'cap' local authority spending but it has
no powers to limit the increase to the local poll tax councils can make to
take account of non-payment in their area.
'I certainly would not be part of a process which sought to gerrymander the
arrangements for electoral advantage. What governments determine to do, they
determine to do, but not for those sort of reasons,' Mr Heseltine said.
Ministers have come under particular pressure to abolish the minimum 20 per
cent payment that people on low incomes must make, both because of the
collection costs and because the requirement would be abolished when the
council tax is introduced to replace the community charge from next April.
Mr Heseltine called on the Commons last night to overturn a government
defeat in the Lords over subjecting local authorities to compulsory
competitive tendering.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, said the next Labour
government would reserve compulsory competitive tendering for circumstances
in which a local authority could be shown, over a period of time, to have
failed to reach acceptable standards.
The Local Government Bill was given a second reading by 276 votes to 221, a
government majority of 55.
</TEXT>
