<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Land deal clearance by Ofwat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Water Services (Ofwat), the economic regulator for the water
industry, has announced that land sales by water companies valued at less
than Pounds 500,000 will no longer have to be submitted for individual
approval.
The disposal of surplus land was a significant political issue in the run-up
to privatisation two years ago. It was then decided that certificates and
valuers' reports had to be submitted for all land sales to third parties
worth more than Pounds 250,000 in London, Pounds 200,000 in the rest of the
south-east and Pounds 150,000 elsewhere.
The stringent rules were set up to ensure that all surplus land was properly
accounted for, and sales were used to offset increases in water charges
required to fund the industry's Pounds 18bn capital investment programme.
Proceeds from any additional sales were to be divided equally between
customers and shareholders of the water companies.
Experience over the past two years has shown that in sales to independent
third parties companies have been under pressure to secure the best price,
and in these sales the interests of customers and shareholders have
coincided. Removal of the certification procedure for small disposals will
mean companies save on costs.
Companies will be required to submit an annual summary to Ofwat on all land
disposals, including transactions below the new Pounds 500,000 threshold.
Ofwat said yesterday that greater scrutiny was still needed of land
transfers made to associated companies within water companies. 'This is an
area where the customers' interests need protecting the most, and so Ofwat
will be redirecting its resources into examining these particular disposals
more thoroughly.'
Strange alliance, Page 25
</TEXT>
