<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Ford to cut discounts to rental companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD is to cut back on deeply discounted sales to the big rental fleet
operators such as Hertz and Avis, whose combined new car purchases - not
just from Ford - approach 100,000 annually.
The rental and leasing industry has been getting cars 'on the cheap' and
Ford intends to 'get back to better margins', Mr Ian McAllister, chairman
and managing director, said yesterday.
Such a course should help Ford to return to profitability this year after
making heavy losses in each of the past two years, Mr McAllister said.
He gave no firm indication of the discounts such companies have received
from Ford. However, a study undertaken for the Retail Motor Industry
Federation, the franchised dealers' trade body, has concluded that discounts
of up to 40 per cent have been available from some manufacturers to some of
the biggest fleets.
A growing number of large fleet deals have also been concluded directly
between manufacturers and fleet operators, bypassing the dealer networks
through which all cars should theoretically be sold.
Such procedures are provoking bitter opposition from the federation, which
has warned that dealer networks could start to disintegrate if the practice
grows much beyond the 200,000 cars a year thought to be subject to such
deals.
Mr McAllister, acknowledging that direct sales could pose a long-term threat
to dealers, indicated that Ford would be less willing than in the past to
involve itself in such deals.
Volvo plan, Page 23
</TEXT>
