FT  21 JAN 92 / Bank steps up EC campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England yesterday stepped up its campaign to make London the
home of the monetary institutions that will be set up as the European
Community moves towards economic and monetary union, Peter Norman writes.
Mr Eddie George, the Bank's deputy governor, said London was the 'logical
location' for future European monetary institutions because of its dominant
position in world foreign exchange markets.
Speaking at a conference organised by Telerate, the financial information
group, Mr George said it would be 'disappointing, though not fatally
damaging, for London' if the institutions went elsewhere.
Britain's commitment to the present parity of sterling in the European
exchange rate mechanism was underlined both by Mr George and by Mr John
Maples, the economic secretary to the Treasury.
