<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / World Trade News: GEC Alsthom wins Pounds 545m Dutch gas
turbine contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GEC ALSTHOM, the Anglo-French power engineering group, yesterday underlined
its growing presence in the world market for large gas turbines by
announcing a Fl 1.75bn (Pounds 545m) contract to supply equipment for a new
Dutch power station.
The deal is GEC Alsthom's biggest turbine order, and forms the lion's share
of a Fl 2bn project planned by Electriciteits Produktiemaatschappij Oost en
Noord-Nederland (Epon), the biggest Dutch electricity supplier. Work begins
this spring on the project at Eems, in the north of the Netherlands. The
1,700MW station will be one of the world's two biggest outside Japan, using
the combined cycle process; waste heat from a gas turbine drives a steam
one, producing greater thermal efficiency and fewer emissions.
The deal is a blow to GEC Alsthom's two big European power generating
equipment rivals, Siemens and Asea Brown Boveri. It confirms the advantage
the Anglo-French group has with its Frame 9F gas turbine, developed jointly
by General Electric of the US and GEC Alsthom's European Gas Turbine Company
(EGT). The 9F is the world's biggest gas turbine, specifically designed for
high performance in combined cycle operation.
Mr Kelvin Bray, EGT chairman, said the latest order, after a recent contract
from National Power in the UK and one with Electricite de France, 'will
allow us to establish the 9F and its derivatives as the turbines for large
combined cycle stations'.
At Eems, EGT will supply five 335MW Vega 109F units, incorporating the gas
turbine, steam turbine and generator on a single shaft. Overall thermal
efficiency will be about 55 per cent, against an average 41 per cent in
existing Dutch power stations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
