<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Turkey details sell-off plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Turkish government plans to sell its shares in five companies, raising
more than Dollars 400m (Pounds 223.4m) in the first stage of its
privatisation programme, writes John Murray Brown in Istanbul.
Officials confirmed yesterday that the stakes would be sold in block shares
to foreign or domestic investors.
A decision by the Council of Ministers last week cleared the way for all
government minority shares in privately managed companies to be sold.
The five companies affected in the first stage are: Ray Insurance, which is
to sell a 40 per cent stake raising TL50bn (Pounds 5.3m); Seker Insurance,
which is to shed 13 per cent of its shares, worth TL7bn; Ipragas, a retail
gas distributor, which will raise Dollars 350m by selling a 51 per cent
stake; Caybank, the tea-planters' co-operative bank, which will shed 49 per
cent for TL315bn; and Tat, a canned fruit company belonging to Koc Holding,
which is expected to fetch TL41bn through its sale of a 17 per cent stake.
</TEXT>
