FT  21 JAN 92 / International Company News: WI Shipping suspends operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TRINIDAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEST INDIES Shipping Corporation (Wisco) has suspended operations after the
seizure of two of its vessels for unpaid bills.
The line, owned by the governments of the Caribbean Community (Caricom), was
being prepared for privatisation when it cancelled its schedule. Government
officials say efforts will be continued to sell the company to private
business in the Caribbean.
The shutdown will adversely affect the Caribbean Community's efforts to
increase intra-regional trade. Wisco traditionally carried over 80 per cent
of the goods traded among Caricom members.
Mr Charles Pennycooke, general manager of the company, said the line's
recent troubles were caused by the failure of the shareholders to pay over
USDollars 7.5m which they had committed to the company.
One vessel was impounded in Miami because of outstanding payments of Dollars
95,000 for leased containers, while another was impounded in Antigua because
of overdue payments of Dollars 80,000 in agent fees. The vessels were
released after shareholders provided Dollars 250,000 to settle outstanding
bills. The line's third vessel is under mandatory docking in Trinidad.
The shareholding governments agreed six months ago to pay off the
outstanding liabilities of the company so that it could be sold. The company
has, however, received only a half of the promised funds, including the
recent payments to secure the release of the impounded vessels.
</TEXT>
