<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's foreign affairs series Assignment (7.45) begins a new run with a
programme about this year's presidential election in the US. Cameras have
been following the main Democrat contenders for the past six months and
Gavin Esler (an excellent reporter on 'Newsnight') assesses their prospects.
Channel 4 screens the third and last part of Brother Felix And The Virgin
Saint, an account of 15th century tourism which has so far proved not only
informative but charming, funny, and sometimes - as in last week's Rules for
Pilgrims (Don't paint your coat of arms on monuments) - astonishing. This
week Brother Felix achieves his life's ambition and reaches the bones of St
Catherine (8.00).
40 Minutes (9.50 BBC2) takes a look at 'real men'. The irony about this
movement in the US (where else) is that it is so obviously a product of the
age of feminism. What do real men do? They hug one another, howl, get in
touch with their childhood selves ..in fact they seem to behave awfully like
feminists, yet we are told this is all a reaction against feminism. Hmm.
Omnibus (10.55 BBC1) tries to decide whether London is a city in crisis.
</TEXT>
