<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Management (In A Nutshell): Venture capital famine forecast
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Small firms may be starved of venture capital finance when the economy
starts to recover following a sharp fall in the amounts of venture capital
raised in 1991, Foreign &amp; Colonial Ventures (F&amp;C), a development capital
fund, has warned.
Independent UK venture capital firms raised only Pounds 400m in new funds
last year, less than half the Pounds 850m raised in 1990 and well below the
Pounds 1.7bn figure the year before that, according to estimates by F&amp;C and
Venture Economics, an industry research group.
Independent venture capital firms have had difficulties raising finance in
the past year because of the poor performance of many of the funds raised
during the 1980s. But the independents account for only part of the venture
capital market and the F&amp;C figures exclude 3i, the largest venture capital
firm, and the 'captive' funds belonging to the banks and other financial
institutions.
The amounts invested by independent venture capitalists also fell last year,
though less sharply, F&amp;C estimated. Investments were Pounds 900m in about
600 companies compared with Pounds 951m put into 618 companies in 1990 and
Pounds 1.2bn into 574 companies the year before that.
</TEXT>
