<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Councils may face challenge over
sick-pay schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL government employers will almost certainly have to introduce sick-pay
schemes for the large number of mainly female, part-time workers earning
less than Pounds 52 a week, as a result of European Community equal pay
legislation.
Mr Stephen Bubb, assistant secretary of the Association of Metropolitan
Authorities, said yesterday that the AMA is concerned that it may not be
treating part-time workers fairly and that it may also be falling foul of EC
legislation.
Almost 70 per cent of the 800,000 local government manual workers are
part-timers and a large number of them fall below Pounds 52 a week. Having
to provide sick-pay for several hundred thousand workers who were previously
excluded could significantly increase pay bills.
Mr Bubb said it was difficult to quantify how many workers would be affected
by an extension of sick-pay schemes but the equality audit being conducted
by employers and unions would probably provide an answer.
The exclusion of part-time workers from sick-pay and other benefits is
likely to be a main theme of this year's local government manual worker
negotiations.
A local government employers' consultation paper, to be distributed this
week, says that the manual workers' interest is likely to shift to equality
issues in this year's negotiations. 'They can be expected in particular to
pursue the position of part-timers' conditions of service,' says the paper.
It continues: 'Already there are indications of concerted union efforts,
through industrial tribunal references, to have the national agreement's
effective exclusion from occupational sick-pay of part-time manual workers
earning less than Pounds 52 a week declared illegal'.
Underlining that point the National Union of Public Employees yesterday
launched a test case at Leeds Industrial Tribunal on behalf of 1,000 school
meals staff employed by North Yorkshire County Council.
Nupe said that following competitive tendering of the school meals service
the council dismissed all its staff and offered them back their jobs on
lower rates of pay, reduced holidays and little or no sick-pay. Nupe is
challenging the action under British and European equal pay laws.
The unions said that the women had been treated differently from groups of
male workers, such as Highways Maintenance, who were also subject to
competitive tendering laws.
Union leaders at Ford New Holland, the tractor maker owned by Ford and Fiat,
will meet this morning to consider whether to order industrial action after
the company said it would not increase a three-year pay deal including a 4
per cent rise in the first year from last November. It warned management
yesterday of the possibility of one or two-day strikes.
</TEXT>
