FT  21 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: News in brief
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WALES: The government's employment record came in for concerted attack in
the Commons yesterday as economic issues dominated proceedings in Welsh
questions.
Mr Barry Jones, shadow Welsh secretary, said that unemployment in the
principality had increased by more than 38,000 since the current recession
began. The government should now apologise for its 'false promises'.
Other parties joined in the assault, with Mr Richard Livsey, the Liberal
Democrats' Welsh spokesman, pointing to rising unemployment in his Brecon
and Radnor con-stituency, and Mr Dafydd Wigley of Plaid Cymru highlighting
the increasing number of applicants for each vacancy.
Mr David Hunt, Welsh secretary, said that Welsh Development International
had recorded 183 projects promising more than 17,000 jobs  - the highest
figure ever.
*****
FREEDOM OF INFORMATION: Liberal Democrats will seek a freedom-of-information
bill early in the next parliament, Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, said
yesterday.
The freedom-of-information proposals supported by the party are set out in a
backbench MP's bill sponsored Mr Archy Kirkwood, Liberal Democrat MP for
Roxburgh and Berwickshire. They would create a general public right of
access to official records held by public authorities, though some
information, for example on defence, would not be disclosed.
