<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / World Trade News: EC in push to revive Gulf free trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EC will today propose to the six states of the Gulf Co-operation Council
(GCC) a speedier phasing-out of import duties on the latter's petrochemical
products, in a move to revive talks for eventual free trade between the two
blocs, David Buchan reports from Brussels.
In the run-up to last year's Gulf war, the GCC states, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and the UAE, rejected proposals by the EC, which
suggested phasing out its import tariffs on Gulf petrochemical products over
16 years.
Spurred by the need to help rebuild Gulf economies, especially Kuwait's,
after the Gulf war, EC governments last autumn decided to risk the wrath of
their own petrochemical lobbies by softening the Community's terms. The
package, which European Commission negotiators will today present to their
GCC counterparts, would do away with the last curbs on petrochemical imports
from the Gulf within 12 years. But no definitive end to the talks is
expected this week.
Some 95 per cent of GCC exports to the EC, totalling Ecu 11.87bn (Pounds
8.4bn) in 1990, enter the EC free, because crude oil and refined products
carry no duty. But the rest, mainly petrochemicals, bear import duties of
6-13 per cent.
</TEXT>
