<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Property companies lead record bankruptcies in Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE collapse of more than 1,000 property companies in Japan last year helped
push corporate bankruptcies to a record high, according to reports published
yesterday by two private credit agencies.
Figures from Teikoku Data Bank and Tokyo Shoko Research show that corporate
liabilities of bankrupt companies last year reached roughly Y8,000bn (Pounds
35bn). This is about four times higher than in 1990, and nearly double the
record set in 1985.
The figures are for corporate bankruptcies of more than Y10m.
The sharp rise in insolvency was a direct result of the Bank of Japan's high
interest rate policy, which was aimed at reversing a steep rise in asset
prices in the last decade that the central bank saw as unhealthy. The high
rates, which the bank began to ease last July, have also sharply slowed the
economy.
Central bank economists have nonetheless repeatedly expressed confidence
that underlying economic activity remained at healthy levels, and that
commercial banks would be able to withstand the steadily rising level of bad
debt on their books.
The conflicting pressures on the economy were underscored by an analysis by
Teikoku Data Bank, showing the second biggest cause of insolvency was the
inability of companies to hire sufficient labour. This accounted for 548
bankruptcies, with debts of Y110.5bn. The central bank has kept interest
rates high in part to combat wage inflation caused by a labour shortage.
Bankruptcies caused by the downturn of property prices accounted for 1,036
cases, with Y2,980bn in liabilities.
The number of insolvencies, while rising from 6,468 cases in 1990 to 10,723
last year, fell well short of the levels of the early 1980s. The number of
bankruptcies with liabilities over Y1bn, however, hit a record 713 cases,
with ll cases over Y10bn.
Teikoku Data Bank said little relief was in sight. December bankruptcies
reached more than 1,200 cases for the first time since March 1987. Total
liabilities of bankrupt companies during the month reached Y868.2bn, the
second highest following the record of Y957.2bn set in August.
The number of property companies filing for bankruptcy in December reached a
monthly high of 119 in spite of recent cuts to the official discount rate
and moves by the government to lift restrictions on property-related
lending.
</TEXT>
