<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 92 / Troops seize key points in Brazzaville
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRAZZAVILLE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MUTINOUS troops in Congo, led by the army high command, controlled key
points in the capital, Brazzaville, yesterday, and demanded the resignation
of reformist Prime Minister Andre Milongo, Reuter reports from Brazzaville.
But sources close to the premier, who had apparently gone into hiding,
claimed he was still in control of the oil-producing central African
country.
Hundreds of armed soldiers were deployed at the radio and television
buildings, the treasury and other key points after demanding the resignation
of Mr Milongo's government on Sunday.
The city was mainly calm but government officials said troops fired in the
air to disperse about 1,000 pro-Milongo demonstrators in the district of
Bas-Congo. Leaflets circulated calling for a general strike against the army
moves.
A military communique broadcast on television said the high command was
meeting leaders of the interim parliament, the High Council of the Republic
(CSR), yesterday afternoon to discuss the crisis.
</TEXT>
